# Multilingual support (i18n)

User-facing text must be **fully localized and consistent** across every supported locale. Treat i18n as a first-class requirement, not an afterthought.

## Supported locales (all required for new keys)

Add every new string to **each** of these `composeResources` directories:

- `values` (English, default)
- `values-fr`, `values-es`, `values-de`, `values-it`
- `values-ar`, `values-ar-rSA`
- `values-nap` (Neapolitan)

Missing a locale breaks parity tests and ships incomplete UX for part of the audience.

## Where strings live

- **Resources only**: `composeApp/src/commonMain/composeResources/values*/strings.xml`
- **UI**: `stringResource(Res.string.<key>, …)` in `@Composable` functions
- **Never** hardcode user-visible English in composables, screen models, domain, or data layers
- **Screen models** expose counts/ids; **composables** format messages (snackbars, summaries, labels)

## Key registry & tests

- Register feature keys in `*StringKeys.kt` (`NutritionStringKeys`, `HomeStringKeys`) when adding a feature area covered by locale tests
- Run `:composeApp:testDebugUnitTest` — includes `NutritionLocaleStringsTest` / home locale parity
- Default `values` strings must be non-blank; placeholders must match across locales (`%1$d`, `%2$s`, same argument order)

## Consistency rules

- Reuse shared helpers for repeated labels (e.g. `nutritionDayLabel()`, meal lunch/dinner keys)
- Use the same terminology across hub, detail screens, and Firebase QA copy for a feature
- **RTL** (`values-ar*`): keep placeholders logical; avoid hard-coded LTR-only layout assumptions
- Language switching via `LanguageManager` / `SupportedAppLanguages` must refresh visible strings (no stale hardcoded cache)

## Review checklist (before PR)

1. Every new/changed `string name` exists in all 8 locale files
2. No new hardcoded UI copy in Kotlin
3. Formatted strings use resources, not manual `.replace()` unless unavoidable in `LaunchedEffect`
4. Locale tests pass; manual spot-check at least English + one non-Latin locale if layout-sensitive
